            <h2>Participles</h2>
            <p><span class="initial-letter darkorange-text">P</span>articiples are forms of the verb that function as adjectives. In modern English there is 
                a present participle, sometimes called the 'ing form' because it ends in <strong>-ing</strong>, and a past participle, which ends in <strong>-ed</strong> and is usually the same as the past singular form of the verb. Although participles are
                used extensively in modern English as verbals in its rather complicated tense system, they are also used as adjectives. Look at the sentences
                below - the first uses the present participle as an adjective, and the second in the formation of the present continuous tense.
                </p>
                <div class="text-center">
                    <div class="grammar-box darkgrey-bg">
                        <div class="inline-block">
                            <span class="red-text big-text border-bottom">I</span><br>
