                </div>
                <p>In Old English, there are also two participles - the past participle ends in <strong>-ende</strong> rather than '-ing',
                and the past particple generally ends in <strong>-ed</strong> or <strong>-od</strong>, and often has the prefix <strong>(ge-)</strong> - often put inside brackets in dictionaries to show that it isn't always used. 
                </p>
                <h3>Participles Used as Verbals</h3>
                <p>The past and present participles are used in the formation of verbal constructions, as they are in modern English. For example 
                the verb 'to be' + participle is often used, as in '<em>Hit wæs ofer stan getimbrod - It was built on stone</em>' or '<em>Hie ymb þa gatu feohtende wæron - 
                They were fighting around the gate</em>', and the auxilliary + participle 
                construction, as in '<em> þu hæfst burh getimbrod- You have built a fortress</em>'.</p>
