                <h3>Participles Used as Adjectives</h3>
                <p>In addition to functioning as verbals, participles can also be used as adjectives - in fact, this is the defining feature 
                    of participles. In modern English we can say 'the leaping salmon' - using a present participle as an adjective modifying 'salmon' - and also
                    'the murdered man' - using a past participle as an adjective.</p>
                    <p>In Old English you commonly find participles used as adjectives,
                    such as in the phrase <em>'slæpende mann - (a) sleeping man'</em>. When participles are used as adjectives, they also
                    decline (take endings) like adjectives, and follow the grammar of the noun they modify. So, in the sentence <em>'He gefeng slǣpendne mann - 
                    He siezed a sleeping man'</em>, the present participle of '<em>slǣpan - to sleep</em>', <em>slæpende</em>, takes the accusative, masculine 
                    <strong>-ne</strong></strong> ending of strong adjectives.
                </p>
                <div class="text-center">
                    <div class="grammar-box darkgrey-bg">
                       
                       
                        
                        <div class="inline-block">
                            <span class="red-text big-text border-bottom">He</span><br>
                            <span class="red-text">Subject</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="inline-block">
                            <span class="green-text big-text"><span class="border-bottom">gefeng</span> </span><br>
                            <span class="green-text">Verb</span>
                        </div> 
                        
                        <div class="inline-block">
                            <span class="green-text big-text"><span class="border-bottom">slæpendne</span> </span><br>
                            <span class="green-text">Participle/Adjective</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="inline-block">
                            <span class="yellow-text big-text border-bottom">mann</span><br>
                            <span class="yellow-text">Direct object</span>
                        </div> 
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <p>
                When a participle is used as an adjective in a weak position (so, after a demonstrative pronoun such as <em>se</em> or a possessive such as 
                <em>his</em>), weak endings are used. In the sentence below, '<em>Grendel gefeng þone slæpendan mann - Grendel grabbed the/that sleeping man</em>',
                the participle adjective <em>slǣpende</em> gets the the accusative singular -an ending of weak adjectives to become <em>slæpendan</em>. 
                </p>
                <div class="text-center">
                    <div class="grammar-box darkgrey-bg">
                       
                       
                        
                        <div class="inline-block">
                            <span class="red-text big-text border-bottom">Grendel</span><br>
                            <span class="red-text">Subject</span>
                        </div>
